# DEML — Cursor Agent Rules (Viking-UI Quality)

You are building the **Data Engineering for Machine Learning (DEML)** platform. Every UI change must follow the final Viking-UI aesthetic: **grid-first modern enterprise SaaS** — Cyber-Noir dark surfaces, Ocean Blue Serenity accents, precision-engineered component anatomy, dense breathable data layouts, restrained dark-first surfaces, and WCAG 2.1 AA by construction. The system should feel calm, precise, premium, and deliberately unsurprising across every product surface.

## Rule hierarchy (read in order)

1. **This file** (`.cursorrules`) — mandatory UI/component behavior for Cursor agents
2. **[THEME.md](THEME.md)** — canonical token matrix, composable component standards
3. **[AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md)** — platform architecture, security, automation invariants
4. **[BOOK.md § Chapter 32](BOOK.md#chapter-32-viking-ui--the-zero-dependency-ui-kit)** — Viking-UI kit narrative, build, publish

Before editing HTML, CSS/SCSS, Tailwind config, or Angular templates: **read THEME.md** for the surfaces you touch.

---

## Styling ownership law (hard gate)

`packages/viking-ui/` is the single source of truth for all DEML styling and UI components. It is the only place where CSS, SCSS, design tokens, static CSS bundles, Web Components, Angular wrappers, icons, and visual utilities may be authored. Application and site surfaces consume Viking-UI; they do not own styling.

- **Do not create or modify custom SCSS/CSS outside `packages/viking-ui/`.** This includes Angular component styles, Astro `<style>` blocks, global app stylesheets, widget-local CSS, Tailwind utility styling, and one-off visual classes.
- **Do not add new styles in `frontend/`, `marketing/`, `viking-ui-docs/`, or `backend/`.** Existing files in those surfaces may only import, load, or receive synced artifacts from the Viking-UI package/build pipeline. If a visual rule is missing, move the rule into `packages/viking-ui/` first.
- **Do not add inline `style=""` attributes** unless the value is non-visual runtime geometry that cannot be represented by a Viking-UI prop or class. If the value affects color, spacing, layout, typography, borders, shadows, motion, or sizing, move it to Viking-UI.
- **Do not introduce new non-Viking visual class systems** in `frontend/`, `marketing/`, `viking-ui-docs/`, Django templates, or static widget consumers. Markup may use `viking-*` elements/classes and semantic content classes only when those classes are styled by the Viking-UI bundle.
- **If a component or pattern is missing, add it to Viking-UI first.** Create framework-neutral Web Components in `packages/viking-ui/src/web/`, Angular wrappers in `packages/viking-ui/src/lib/` when needed, and shared surface styles under `packages/viking-ui/src/styles/`. Decompose monolithic surface files into focused partials (`_alerts.scss`, `_severity-pills.scss`, etc.) loaded by a single `@use` index — never grow a single surface file past ~300 lines.
- **Consume Viking-UI through published/public entrypoints only.** Apps must use the npm package or workspace alias (`@dataengineeringformachinelearning/viking-ui` and documented subpaths); browser/static consumers should use the built package artifacts and jsDelivr CDN where possible.
- **After changing Viking-UI styles or components, rebuild and sync** with `npm run build:viking-ui:package` and `python scripts/sync_design_system.py` so all consuming surfaces receive the same artifacts. Never commit Viking-UI style changes without verifying the downstream surfaces build cleanly.
- **Uniformity sweeps:** Before shipping, grep all consuming surfaces for orphaned app-local styles, raw hex, ad-hoc breakpoints, or `<div class="card">` / `<div class="alert">` outliers. Run `node scripts/enforce-theme.js` — zero violations means zero violations. Any outlier is a blocking defect.

Consuming apps may compose UI, bind data, pass props/attributes, and choose existing Viking-UI variants. They may not define the visual implementation.

---

## Final aesthetic standard

Viking-UI must read as **grid-first modern enterprise SaaS** — calm, precise, premium, and deliberately unsurprising. Implemented only through `packages/viking-ui/`.

- **Aerospace-command precision:** premium engineering feel, exact alignment, low-noise hierarchy, and deterministic rhythm. Surfaces feel engineered, durable, and expensive — never startup-neutral or whimsical.
- **Geometric severity, not fantasy:** austere geometry, cold materiality, and sparse restraint. Severe silhouettes and structural accents only — never themed illustration, faux-medieval ornament, glassmorphism, neon cyberpunk, or decorative storytelling.
- **Dark-first command surfaces:** deep navy/charcoal backgrounds, machined metallic borders, restrained electric-teal for command/confirmation, rich crimson for escalation and danger. No gradient orbs, neon glow, mesh backgrounds, or decorative clutter on base surfaces.
- **Boring consistency:** templates, grids, and semantic tokens make every route feel like one coherent enterprise product. Zero visual drift under pressure.
- **Quiet surface depth:** crisp one-pixel borders, stepped surfaces (`--viking-navy-*` scale via `--viking-charcoal-*` aliases), and soft low-elevation shadows distinguish hierarchy through token stepping, never stacked opacity.

**Directional references** (inform contracts, never import runtimes):
- [Material Design 3](https://m3.material.io/) — adaptive foundations, accessible state clarity.
- [Flux UI](https://fluxui.dev/) — composable layouts, dense but breathable data surfaces.
- [Spartan](https://spartan.ng/) — clean Angular primitive language, accessible composition, SSR-safe behavior.
- [shadcn/ui](https://ui.shadcn.com/) — explicit component anatomy, composable blocks.
- [Cloudscape](https://cloudscape.design/) — AWS-scale operational density, fluid responsive layouts.
- [Trust Controls](https://www.trustcontrols.ai/) — evidence-minded security governance UX.

**Implementation boundary:** every style, token, wrapper, Web Component, chart treatment, or visual utility belongs in `packages/viking-ui/`; app folders only consume the result.

Translate the aesthetic into concrete UI: machined metallic borders, dark steel surfaces, electric-teal command accents, crimson escalation, compact telemetry panels, native SVG charts with generous inlay spacing, readable tables/forms, and strategic geometric dividers. Data dominates ornament. Context determines density — dashboards use metric-card/chart-panel inlay, settings use form-section/field stacks, static sections use wider readable widths. Never force one density pattern into another context.

DEML brand artwork is the narrow static-asset exception: logos, favicons, application icons, and social previews use `--viking-brand-navy` (`#070C20`) and `--viking-brand-blue` (`#0078FF`). Do not use those literals as app-local product styling; product UI continues through semantic Viking-UI tokens.

---

## Composable primitive quality (structure, not palette)

Viking-UI follows a **composable primitive** model: install behavior in Angular, style from package-owned tokens/components, and avoid app-local styling entirely.

| Pattern                  | Viking-UI equivalent                                                   | You must                                                     |
| ------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Card surfaces            | `viking-card`, `viking-metric-card`, `viking-hud-panel`                | Use these — never raw `<div class="card">`                   |
| Form field stack         | `viking-field` → control (`viking-input`, `viking-select`, …)          | Compose every input through `viking-field`                   |
| Button variants          | `viking-button` (`primary`, `secondary`, `outline`, `danger`, `ghost`) | Never hand-roll button styles                                |
| Dark-first shell         | `data-theme="dark"` default                                            | Preserve dark-first; light mode shifts lightness only        |
| Accessible focus         | `--viking-ring` 2px + 2px offset                                       | Never remove `:focus-visible` for aesthetics                 |
| Settings / billing forms | `viking-form-section` + grouped `viking-field`                         | Section rhythm: `--viking-space-3` / `--viking-font-size-lg` |
| Charts                   | `viking-chart` + `viking-chart-panel` (native SVG, zero deps)          | Never canvas, D3, Chart.js, or ApexCharts wrappers           |
| Chart inlay              | `viking-chart-panel[loading]`, `viking-chart-empty-state`              | Loading/empty states are mandatory — no bare SVG              |
| Series colors            | `VIKING_SERIES_PRESETS` from `series-presets.ts`                       | Never raw hex in chart code — use `--viking-series-1`…`8`   |
| Skeleton loaders         | `viking-skeleton`, `viking-loading-overlay`, `viking-progress`         | Never generic CSS spinners                                   |
| Feedback                 | `viking-toast`, `viking-callout`, `viking-badge`                       | Never `alert()` or ad-hoc div banners                       |
| Peer surface layouts     | `viking-panel-grid`                                                     | Equal-height cards, HUD panels, and charts by construction   |
| Form field layouts       | `viking-form-grid`                                                      | Top-align fields even when helper/error copy differs         |
| Vertical rhythm          | `viking-stack`                                                         | Never add one-off sibling margins between content blocks     |
| Section anatomy          | `viking-section-template`                                              | Reuse title, description, actions, divider, and body rhythm  |
| Page layouts             | `viking-page-shell` → `viking-section` + semantic layout recipe       | Never rebuild package breakpoints or gutters locally        |

**Context-aware density:** Dashboards and analytics pages use `viking-metric-card`, `viking-hud-panel`, and `viking-chart-panel` for dense data inlay. Settings and billing forms use `viking-form-section` with grouped `viking-field` stacks. Status/overview surfaces use open card layouts (`viking-card` with generous padding). Static/open sections (marketing, docs) use wider readable widths (`--viking-content-readable-max-width`). Never force a dashboard density pattern into a settings form, or vice versa.

**Intentional palette:** **deep navy/charcoal surfaces, dark steel metallic borders, restrained electric-teal/crimson accents** — grid-first modern enterprise SaaS, not startup-neutral.

